{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17632006","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17632006"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T17:35:46+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T17:35:46+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17415"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17415","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17415"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10105"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"70527"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10105","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10105"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17415"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"55991"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"5326"},{"type":"tags","id":"5540"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"23668"},{"type":"contributions","id":"23673"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"70527","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/70527"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EUtilitarianism is one of the major frameworks used in healthcare ethics and public health decision-making.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the fundamental principle of utilitarianism?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Actions should respect individual autonomy above all","Actions should follow predetermined moral rules","Actions should be judged by the intentions of the actor","Actions should prioritise the needs of the most vulnerable","Actions should maximise benefit for the greatest number of people"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe fundamental principle of utilitarianism is that \u003Cstrong\u003Eactions should maximise benefit for the greatest number of people\u003C/strong\u003E. This ethical framework evaluates the morality of actions based on their consequences and overall societal impact, rather than on rigid rules or individual intentions.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EActions should respect individual autonomy above all\u003C/strong\u003E describes principlism with emphasis on autonomy, which may conflict with utilitarian goals of maximising collective benefit.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EActions should follow predetermined moral rules\u003C/strong\u003E describes deontological ethics, which focuses on duty and moral rules rather than consequences.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EActions should be judged by the intentions of the actor\u003C/strong\u003E contradicts utilitarianism\u0027s focus on outcomes rather than intentions.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EActions should prioritise the needs of the most vulnerable\u003C/strong\u003E describes an egalitarian or justice-based approach, which may sometimes conflict with utilitarian goals.\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EUtilitarianism is particularly relevant in public health where decisions often need to balance individual interests against population benefit, such as in vaccination programmes or resource allocation during pandemics.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Utilitarianism is an ethical framework that judges the morality of actions based on their consequences and overall benefit to society.","The core principle of utilitarianism is to maximise happiness or well-being for the greatest number of people.","Utilitarianism considers the outcomes of actions rather than the intentions behind them."],"references":["Shultz JM, Sullivan LM, Galea S. Public Health: An Introduction to the Science and Practice of Population Health. Springer Publishing Company; 2021."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"55991"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17415"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"55991","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/55991"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-15T19:00:56+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-04T00:10:30+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10105"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"70527"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"5326","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/5326"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf0f","name":"Public Health","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"c